<TEXT>
a group of 47 disabled 
guerrillas left late saturday for cuba under protection of the 
mexican government and the red cross government and airport 
officials said 
the 47 mostly amputees belong to the farabundo marti national 
liberation front they occupied the capitals metropolitan 
cathedral for six weeks then on tuesday moved into the mexican 
embassy in their efforts to leave the country 
in mexico the foreign ministry said in a statement the group 
accompanied by two nurses was headed for cuba 
the statement said the group left tonight on a special red 
cross flight for cuba where they have asked to be taken to receive 
special medical attention 
officials at salvadors international airport said the 47 left 
on a plane chartered by the mexican government 
officials from the mexican embassy red cross or salvadoran 
government would not speak to reporters saturday the guerrillas 
also were told not to speak to the press 
but one guerrilla identified only as israel told reporters 
were going to leave for cuba 
israel who lost a leg in combat said the group hoped to 
receive medical care in cuba 
it could not be determined whether the disabled men most of 
them young received political asylum in cuba 
monsignor arturo rivero damas the archbishop of san salvador 
called the evacuation one of the points of humanization in the 
conflict 
late last month rivera damas appealed for the guerrillas to 
vacate his church saying the cathedral is not a hotel 
salvadors government said 2000 soldiers 500 guerrillas and 
700 civilians have been disabled in combat during the more than 
nine years of civil war leftist rebels have fought the succession 
of usbacked governments for nearly 10 years 
since 1984 346 guerrillas have been evacuated to other 
countries including france sweden and west germany the last 
evacuation occurred in may 
