<TEXT>
the government is preparing orders that will 
force airlines to regularly strip the interiors of their aging 
jetliners for corrosion inspections 
rules are also being considered to require all new airliner 
models to undergo pressurized tests on a sample aircraft that would 
batter the fuselage with the equivalent of two lifetimes of 
takeoffs and landings 
these and other steps to ensure the safety of airliners that are 
increasingly used long past their designed lifespans were presented 
at a threeday industry and government conference last week 
more than 300 aviation experts at the second annual 
international conference on aging aircraft viewed slides of 
deteriorating jetliners discussed an array of sophisticated 
detection equipment and exchanged horror stories including the 
supposed discovery of a dead frog in a corrosionprone jetliner 
section now referred to as the guppy pond 
with the us fleet of passenger jets exceeding 12 years old and 
expected to grow older as the demand pushes airlines to refurbish 
rather than retire their oldest models federal aviation 
administration officials disclosed plans for new airworthiness 
directives to deal with corrosion in boeing 747 737 727 and 707 
jetliners 
the orders are expected next month to be followed in february 
1990 by similar directives affecting mcdonnell douglasbuilt jets 
and later for other aircraft said leroy keith head of the faas 
air certification directorate in seattle 
there are no plans for mandatory retirement ages but the cost 
will be going up in maintaining aging aircraft keith said 
the corrosion orders are based on the work of an 
industrygovernment task force that already has triggered sweeping 
changes in the way older airliners are kept safe 
both industry and government officials stress that none of the 
steps indicate that airliners now in service are unsafe but are an 
effort to ensure against failures before dangers arise 
since the task force was set up at the first aging airliner 
conference sponsored by the faa and the industrybacked flight 
safety foundation 16 months ago the government has ordered 
mandatory replacements of parts on jetliners as they reach a set 
number of takeoffs and landings previously the faa ordered 
repetitive inspections with replacements required only when 
problems were found 
those orders focused primarily on problems related to metal 
fatigue as an airliner is pressurized for flight and depressurized 
upon landing 
the new directives which are expected to be adopted in other 
countries where usbuilt airliners fly will require carriers to 
set up their own anticorrosion programs with inspections on 
various sections of each airliner at intervals ranging from three 
to eight years 
corrosion is more closely related than fatigue to chronological 
age the quality of care the airliner is given the environment in 
which it is flown and conditions within the aircraft 
frequent coffee spills in the galley or regular hauling of fish 
or animal products in the cargo hold for example can accelerate 
corrosion 
no airliner model is immune to deterioration said government 
scientist pin tong 
multiplesite damage is not isolated to one manufacturer or 
one model but may appear anywhere in the aging fleet he said 
both boeing and mcdonnell douglas have conducted extensive tests 
on selected models to determine how many takeoffs and landings an 
airliner can undergo without damage 
a dc9 fuselage went through the equivalent of more than 200000 
flights with no evidence of multiplesite fatigue damage said 
dan hagemaier a douglas aircraft engineer 
faa officials said rules requiring such testing for all new 
aircraft models are being drawn up and could affect future design 
the air line pilots association has been calling for such tests 
to set design service life for airliners 
alpa proposes that any extension of the service life be 
certified only after a teardown inspection of a representative 
aircraft 
j a marceau a boeing corrosion expert said more than 75 
percent of corrosion problems been solved in new passenger planes 
rolling off the assembly line 
we have the majority of problems licked with new design 
philosophies he said 
the new corrosion orders will classify damage at three levels 
including the earliest signs localized damage and extensive 
deterioration 
an airline will have to open its planes up inspect repair 
anything thats found report the findings to the government apply 
corrosiveprevention compounds and then close it up said owen 
schrader faa aging aircraft program manager at the certification 
office in seattle 
the goal is to require inspections frequently enough that 
eventually we wont find anything but levelone corrosion he 
said 
the orders could prove costly to some carriers but schrader 
said most major airlines already have anticorrosion programs and 
the required inspections could be done along with other mandatory 
work 
the goal is to find an inexpensive means of quickly checking 
whole airliners for both cracks and corrosion without tearing them 
apart 
faa and national aeronautics and space administration scientists 
indicated significant research still is needed with a number of 
methods being tested and used in current inspections 
but schrader said the only acceptable detection device for the 
mandatory corrosion inspections is likely to be the human eye 
</TEXT>
