trains saturday night in armenia said azerbaijani activist shahin 
gadzhiev 
gadzhiev identified himself as a spokesman for the azerbaijani 
peoples front other members of the peoples front denied that 
train traffic had been halted 
the trains are running but the attacks on them are also 
continuing adel mamedov said in a telephone interview from the 
azerbaijani capital of baku 
tass the official soviet news agency reported late sunday that 
37 trains had been dispatched from azerbaijan to armenia over the 
past day and a half but it said extremist forces are still 
hindering the normal functioning of the route 
about 400 trains with a total of 60000 cars have been reported 
idled on main lines in the southwestern region of the soviet union 
the soviet legislature imposed a temporary ban on strikes in 
such key sectors as transport and energy tuesday after president 
mikhail s gorbachev warned that stoppages could ruin the economy 
and lead to anarchy 
it also ordered the ministries of defense and interior to 
restore rail traffic between the two feuding caucasus republics 
troops moved in to protect the trains and soviet media said friday 
the twomonth blockade that crippled armenia was over 
but the measures failed to quell the prolonged ethnic feuding 
over nagornokarabakh the fertile region claimed by both armenia 
and azerbaijan 
the christian armenian enclave has been part of moslemdominated 
azerbaijan since 1923 
nineteen months of unrest over nagornokarabakh has left 117 
dead thousands injured and more than 2000 homes and apartments 
destroyed tass said 
in the disputed region five people were wounded in clashes 
saturday and an epidemic of viral hepatitis threatened the 
population tass reported sunday 
mutual hostility blinds the participants of the conflict with 
dark malice and suppresses their reason the official news agency 
said noting that reports from the region increasingly resemble 
dispatches from war zones 
airlifts are the only thing preventing mass starvation in 
nagornokarabakh which has a predominantly armenian population of 
about 160000 tass said 
it said a highway bridge on the outskirts of nagornokarabakhs 
capital stepanakert was blown up early saturday cutting off 
additional areas 
ungathered grape crops are rotting in the field armed attacks 
against villages continue and ambulances cannot respond to calls 
because they have no gas tass said 
armenian activist rafael popoyan said sunday that armenia was 
still hit by food and fuel shortages although they were not as 
severe as in nagornokarabakh 
he said the few shipments that made it through azerbaijan to 
armenia were sabotaged they either contained damaged materials or 
cisterns filled with water instead of fuel 
everything that arrived is no good he said in a telephone 
interview from the armenian capital of yerevan that the blockade 
was stopped at all is a myth 
interior ministry officials and reporters for staterun media in 
armenia and azerbaijan were unavailable sunday for comment on the 
blockade 
about 80 percent of armenian rail traffic runs through 
azerbaijan the azerbaijani blockade has virtually halted 
reconstruction work on armenian areas destroyed by the massive 
earthquake last december that left 25000 dead 
