seasons will open the world series at home next saturday against 
the winner of the national league playoff either the san francisco 
giants or the chicago cubs 
before sunday nights game san francisco had a 21 lead over 
chicago in the bestofseven playoff 
dave stewart outpitched dave stieb for the second time in the 
american league series as oakland became the first team to win 
consecutive league titles since the new york yankees and the los 
angeles dodgers each did it in 197778 
oaklands rickey henderson stole the series and was named most 
valuable player henderson got on base 14 times in 23 plate 
appearances andof the creditworthiness of the soviet union by 
standard amp poors corp or another creditrating firm would be an 
important boost for the soviet union should it try to tap the us 
bond market as part of its modernization drive 
the soviet union returned to foreign bond markets for the first 
time in 70 years when it sold a debt issue in switzerland in 
january 1988 since then it has sold five more bond issues in 
western europe mostly to banks for a total of about 850 million 
worth of borrowing according to sampp 
but it has yet to attempt a bond issue in the united states one 
reason is that it must first settle about 193 million worth of 
bonds sold by czarist russia to the us government to help finance 
russian participation in world war i after the 1917 revolution 
the new soviet government repudiated the bonds and has yet to make 
good on them 
under us law the soviets are barred from selling bonds here 
until they settle this old debt 
a 1986 settlement with great britain over a similar czarist bond 
offering bodes well for negotiations now under way with the state 
department on the us bonds sampp said 
the credit rating agency said many problems stand in the way of 
assessing the investment risk of soviet bonds 
among them are the unreliable and incomplete nature of soviet 
government statistics lack of comparability between some soviet 
and western economic data and the lack of firm figures on total 
soviet borrowings in the west 
right now analyzing the soviet economy is a game of 
estimations said philip bates an sampp analyst its a new 
frontier to some degree 
bates declined to comment on whether soviet officials have 
agreed to cooperate with a credit analysis should sampp decide to do 
one but he said its a little difficult to obtain that 
information without being able to talk to the government about it 
a credit rating is important because it helps investors 
determine the chances that their money will be repaid when a bond 
come due it also gives them an idea of the rate of interest they 
should require to tie up their money 
ironically the attempts of soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
to restructure his nations economy called perestroika could harm 
the countrys oncesterling credit standing among western bankers 
who have loaned it money since the early 1970s with perestroika 
has come instability and an economic downturn 
the system that was in place gave bankers a lot of confidence 
in the soviet governments ability to repay their obligations 
bates said 
however he said it appears that much of the soviet 
governments ability to adjust the nations balanceofpayments 
figures in order to repay foreign debt remain in place 
a book published earlier this year is skeptical of the soviet 
unions recent western borrowing the coming soviet crash 
gorbachevs desperate pursuit of credit in western financial 
markets contends that soviet economic statistics are extremely 
unreliable and that assumptions about the nations ability to repay 
its debt may be erroneous 
the author hoover institution researcher judy shelton also 
criticizes the popular belief that the west is accelerating 
gorbachevs reforms by loaning money she contends that instead of 
reducing military spending or making other tough economic choices 
the soviets are looking abroad for the cash to pay for perestoika 
while preserving their military might 
sampps chief competitor moodys investors service inc has not 
rated the soviet union either but it recently released a credit 
study of hungary another east bloc nation undergoing economic 
liberalization hungary also has been selling bonds in the west 
moodys analyst michael van bemmelen said obtaining the required 
information about hungary took longer than the time spent for 
similar evaluations of western nations but he said his company is 
confident about the results 
though there were problems in obtaining government data about 
the domestic hungarian economy he said most of the determinants 
of the creditworthiness are really in its relationship to western 
countries 
that type of information is available from several sources he 
said including international banks and exporters and importers 
but van bemmelen said he could foresee additional problems in 
rating the soviet union such as valuing its huge gold holdings 
the soviet government does not disclose that amount 
